         <abstract>
            <p>An AICPA Research Study (#4) and an Accounting Principals Board Opinion (#5) focused attention on discounting lease payments in order to determine the amount at which long term leases should be valued. The authors concluded however, that since a long-term lease is essentially a means of financing the acquisition of an asset, the asset should be capitalized at what it would have cost if purchased and the financing costs entailed in the lease alternative should be treated as interest expense. Only if an arms' length purchase price is not available do the author's recommend use of discounting and at a rate equal to the lessee's approximate borrowing cost. Some attention is given to evaluations concerning unique assets, third party lessors, second hand assets and leases for portions of an assets life.</p>
          </abstract>
